title: For Sale:  12 Gauge Franchi Affinity Semi-Auto Shotgun, 26" Black Synthetic
postcontent:
Hello, I am interested in selling my very lightly used black synthetic 26" 12 gauge Franchi Affinity shotgun that I bought this past summer.  I have the gun manual, warranty card, choke tubes, choke tube wrench, and shim kit that came with the gun.  Nothing is wrong with it and its in excellent condition...just looking to get something that I think will fit me a little better for the upcoming waterfowl season.  I have only used it in on a round of sporting clays and for the opening day of dove season so there have only been about 3 boxes of shells total through this gun.

This thing is tough to find in stores because a) it is a great price for a semi-auto shotgun b) it is made in Italy by Benelli (Franchi is part of the company) and c) it has received some really positive reviews from gun experts (http://www.fieldandstream.com/blogs/gun-nuts/2012/06/good-shotguns-franchi-affinity) so hopefully somebody out there is interested.  For those that aren't familiar it is very, very similar to Benelli's M2 and even incorporates the Inertia Driven technology that is well known for its reliability.

Please feel free to ask me any questions - I will be more than happy to answer them.  I will also provide pics if you are interested.

Some helpful online links of the gun:

http://www.franchiusa.com/franchi-affinity-shotgun/
http://www.chuckhawks.com/franchi_affinity_shotgun.htm
http://www.gunsandammo.com/reviews/shotgun-safari-franchi-affinity-franchi-instinct-reviews/
http://www.fieldandstream.com/blogs/gun-nuts/2012/06/good-shotguns-franchi-affinity

title: For Sale:  Spike's Tactical 5.45x39 complete upper with NiB bolt carrier group
postcontent:
I have for sale a lightly-used Spike's Tactical 5.45x39 upper. The barrel, flash hider, and gas system are Melonite-treated for corrosion resistance while the bolt and carrier have been coated with Nickel Boron for the ultimate in wear and rust protection. The bolt and receiver are marked with the Spike's Tactical logo while the left side of the upper is marked "5.45x39" for easy identification. 

I purchased this upper new and put about 200 rounds total through it during two range sessions (making sure the upper was cleaned and oiled after both, as you can see in the image below the bore is still bright and shiny.) I was very pleased with both the performance of the upper and the very low cost of the round, but as I have recently been bequeathed the reloading equipment and large component stash of a relative I've instead decided to reload 5.56 for my cheap plinking needs. 

With Russian steel-cased .223 still near 40 cents per round surplus 5.45 is currently the best deal in centerfire rifle ammo. If you don't reload but still want to shoot your AR-15 it's the way to go right now as AIM and Palmetto are currently selling it as low as 16.6 cents per round shipped. The future outlook for surplus importation from Russia is good while new production ammo is available from Wolf, Bear, and Hornady. I have available 210 rounds of 7n6 Russian ammo as well, which I would be willing to sell for an additional $36.

Please note that although you can usually get 5.45 to feed from Lancers or USGI mags when downloaded to only about 10 rounds, this upper requires special ASC 5.45 magazines if you'd like to load and fire a full 30 rounds per mag. Unfortunately I've already sold mine but on the plus side it appears J&G Surplus has them in stock for $10 each. 

This comes with both the FDE Magpul handguards and stock round carbine handguards pictured. I can meet you in St. Peters or St. Charles, my preferred spot for FTF sales is at Bass Pro Shops or Cabelas.
